# ============================================================
# AZURE COST OPTIMIZER - CONFIGURATION GUIDE
# ============================================================
# 
# This file shows how to configure the Azure Cost Optimizer
# to work with any Azure account/subscription
#
# ============================================================
# AZURE ACCOUNT CONFIGURATION
# ============================================================
#
# To use with YOUR Azure account, follow these steps:
#
# 1. In Azure Portal, go to: Azure AD / App Registrations
# 2. Create a new App Registration (or use existing)
# 3. Copy these values:
#
# TENANT_ID
#   - Where: Azure Portal > Azure Active Directory > Overview > Tenant ID
#   - What: Your organization's unique Azure AD identifier (GUID)
#   - Example: xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx
#
TENANT_ID=YOUR_TENANT_ID

# CLIENT_ID
#   - Where: App Registration > Overview > Application ID
#   - What: The app's unique identifier
#   - Example: xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx
#
CLIENT_ID=YOUR_CLIENT_ID

# CLIENT_SECRET
#   - Where: App Registration > Certificates & secrets > New client secret
#   - What: The app's password (create a new one if needed)
#   - SECURITY: Never commit this to version control!
#   - Example: YourSecretKeyHere_ReplaceWithActualSecret
#
CLIENT_SECRET=YOUR_CLIENT_SECRET

# SUBSCRIPTION_ID
#   - Where: Any resource in your subscription > Overview > Subscription ID
#   - What: The Azure subscription to analyze
#   - Example: xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx
#   - Note: You can analyze multiple subscriptions by changing this
#
SUBSCRIPTION_ID=YOUR_SUBSCRIPTION_ID

# ============================================================
# GITHUB MODELS API CONFIGURATION
# ============================================================
#
# Required to use GitHub's inference models (free tier available)
#
# GITHUB_PAT
#   - Where: GitHub > Settings > Developer settings > Personal access tokens > Tokens (classic)
#   - Scopes needed: api (for accessing inference)
#   - What: Your GitHub authentication token
#   - Note: Keep this SECRET, never commit it
#
GITHUB_PAT=github_pat_XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX

# GITHUB_MODEL_ENDPOINT
#   - What: GitHub's model inference API endpoint
#   - Default: https://models.inference.ai.azure.com/
#   - Note: This is the standard GitHub model endpoint
#
GITHUB_MODEL_ENDPOINT=https://models.inference.ai.azure.com/

# GITHUB_MODEL
#   - What: Which AI model to use for analysis
#   - Options: gpt-4o-mini, gpt-4o (check GitHub for available models)
#   - Default: gpt-4o-mini (faster, good for cost analysis)
#   - Note: gpt-4o-mini is recommended for faster responses with GitHub free tier
#
GITHUB_MODEL=gpt-4o-mini

# ============================================================
# HOW TO GET STARTED
# ============================================================
#
# Step 1: Set up Azure Authentication
#   1.1. Go to Azure Portal
#   1.2. Create or use an App Registration
#   1.3. Grant it "Reader" role on your subscription:
#        - Go to Subscriptions > Your Subscription > Access Control (IAM)
#        - Click "Add role assignment" 
#        - Select "Reader" role
#        - Assign to your app
#
# Step 2: Set up GitHub Models API
#   2.1. Go to GitHub.com
#   2.2. Create a classic Personal Access Token (PAT)
#   2.3. Copy the entire token value
#
# Step 3: Update this file
#   3.1. Replace all YOUR_* values with your actual values
#   3.2. Save as .env in the project root
#   3.3. Never share or commit this file with git
#
# Step 4: Install dependencies
#   python -m pip install -r requirements.txt
#
# Step 5: Run the application
#   uvicorn main:app --reload
#
# ============================================================
# USING WITH MULTIPLE AZURE SUBSCRIPTIONS
# ============================================================
#
# Option 1: Switch subscriptions by changing SUBSCRIPTION_ID
#   - Simply update SUBSCRIPTION_ID in .env
#   - Restart the application
#
# Option 2: Store multiple credentials
#   - Create multiple .env files (.env.production, .env.dev, etc.)
#   - Use: python main.py --env .env.production
#   - This requires modifying main.py to support --env flag
#
# ============================================================
# REQUIRED PERMISSIONS FOR AZURE APP
# ============================================================
#
# The app needs these roles on your subscription:
#   - "Reader": Read access to all resources
#   - "Cost Management Reader" (optional): Enhanced cost data access
#   - "Billing Reader" (optional): Better billing insights
#
# How to assign:
#   1. Azure Portal > Subscriptions > Access Control (IAM)
#   2. "Add role assignment"
#   3. Select role
#   4. Select your App Registration
#   5. Save
#
# ============================================================
# SECURITY BEST PRACTICES
# ============================================================
#
# ⚠️  IMPORTANT:
#   - Never commit .env to GitHub/version control
#   - Use .gitignore to exclude .env files
#   - Rotate client secrets regularly (every 90 days)
#   - Use Azure Key Vault for production deployments
#   - Limit role assignments to only what's needed
#   - Regularly review and revoke unused app registrations
#
# ============================================================
